snippet.textDisplay:
Few points
1. If you ask any F1 fan what do they miss about F1, it's not the speed. It's the sound of V8 and V10 and battles. So speed flies out of the window.
2. The average F1 race is 305 km. The average Formula-E race is 4-5 km. Unless it's not hybrid, no way any electric car keeps the performance in the long run with current battery technologies.
3. Racing tournaments are a combination of speed and endurance. It's not about breaking lap records. No pure electric car has balls to compete in F1, Le Mans or NASCAR. And I personally enjoy the sound of engines and battles, not the vacuum cleaner sounds. Technologies will change the situation of course but there is still a way to go.

snippet.textDisplay:
Yep, been discussing this among friends for about 12 months now, most of the big car manufacturers has given a date when they will be selling all electric cars, which started us thinking - what is the purpose of F1 if the internal combustion engine (ICE) will be dead in about 10 years? can it stay as the pinnacle of motorsport but be electric? there's different variations of open wheel racing around the world today, why not different variations of electric cars? Formula E are spec cars, would manufacturers be allowed to "run wild" in electric F1? as for the noise, why can't they just make an artificial noise? BMW (and I think Audi in their diesels) do it in their road cars, why not replicate the sound of a screaming V12?!?


 Makes you wonder, Bernie see the writing on the wall and sell out and bail at the perfect time?

snippet.textDisplay: F1 has already lost almost all of my interest at this point so I don't really care unfortunately. Maybe they would gain it back if some of big manufacturers pulled out to go make their electric snow flake motors and f1 had to divert back to a modern, somewhat affordable version of a gasoline burning V8 like the Cosworth. But that's just my opinion. Very rarely do I watch current F1 races. As of lately I've been hooked on watching retro F1 and I love it! Mid 70s to late 80s is without a doubt the best era of the sport. The cars were crazy/awesome looking, sounded amazing, and very dangerous! They might not be as quick around the circuits as modern day F1 but, more entertaining to watch for me. The huge diversity of the cars and their power plants, and the courageous drivers that had the guts to pilot them has intrigued me for the past year or so. YouTube and Duke video have been great sources for plenty of insight into the "Dangerous years of Formula 1."

snippet.textDisplay: Speed and handling are only a small, SMALL part of what I love about cars. The the cars "presence", that is the theater of the machine, is what I love about them. That means the sound, the look, the knowledge that there are thousands of highly machined moving parts inside it. In this essence an electric car is just a box with some wires in it compared to an ICE machine. And when I talk about sound, I mean "hearing protection required at 20 yards away" kind of sound. Not a simple electric shaver in the same room sound. I also love the fact that you can make an ICE COMPLETELY yours! And the fact it takes skill to do so. I can say that there is no other car exactly like mine on the planet, and that  I did it myself. When I can upgrade my car with only a firmware update, and changing a few wires out, changing some 1's to 0's in a computer program or (worse yet) buy one just like it from the factory, that's the instant cars die as a passion and become just yet another fucking tech gadget to be used and then thrown away when you're done.

false.
the metals mined for the batteries are horrifyingly toxic to the workers mining and the environment at large.
